{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17592890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17592890"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:19:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:19:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15282"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15282","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15282"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0,0.06,0,0.74]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7973"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80806"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7973","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7973"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15282"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66126"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"8745"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19400"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27594"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80806"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPorto-systemic anastomoses are connections between the portal venous system and the systemic venous system. These anastomoses can become clinically significant in certain conditions affecting the liver.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about porto-systemic anastomoses is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["They facilitate portal blood directly entering the inferior vena cava","They are primarily located in the pelvis","They are responsible for the formation of haemorrhoids","They are not affected by portal hypertension","They can lead to varices in the oesophagus and rectum"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPorto-systemic anastomoses are normal connections between the portal and systemic venous systems. Portal hypertension describes a situation where blood flow through the portal venous system has become impeded (most commonly due to cirrhosis). As a consequence, these anastomoses can become engorged and dilated, facilitating the passage of blood back to the systemic venous system. In turn, this venous dilatation leads to the formation of varices, particularly in the \u003Cstrong\u003Eoesophagus\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Erectum\u003C/strong\u003E. Whilst often asymptomatic, these varices can be a source of significant bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe major sites of porto-systemic anastomoses are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELower end of the oesophagus (oesophageal branch of left gastric vein and azygous)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUpper part of the anal canal (superior and inferior rectal veins)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERetroperitoneum (mesenteric and retroperitoneal veins)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EParaumbilical (portal and anterior abdominal wall veins)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPorto-systemic anastomoses are found in the\u003Cstrong\u003E pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E, but they are not the primary location. They exist in the upper part of the anal canal, connecting the superior rectal veins (portal) to inferior and middle rectal veins (systemic). There is no direct communication with the \u003Cstrong\u003Einferior vena cava\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst \u003Cstrong\u003Ehaemorrhoids\u003C/strong\u003E can be related to increased venous pressure, they are not directly caused by porto-systemic anastomoses.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Porto-systemic anastomoses are connections between the portal and systemic venous systems.","These anastomoses can become engorged and form varices in conditions like portal hypertension.","Common sites of porto-systemic anastomoses include the oesophagus, rectum, and umbilicus."],"references":["Nightingale, J. M. (2012). Applied anatomy and physiology of the gastrointestinal tract (GIT). Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book: Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book, 45.","Podolsky, D. K., Camilleri, M., Fitz, J. G., Kalloo, A. N., Shanahan, F., \u0026 Wang, T. C. (Eds.). (2015). Yamada\u0027s textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66126"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15282"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66126","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66126"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-23T08:59:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-23T09:01:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7973"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80806"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"ty